{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639558"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:06:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.9,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10491"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24490"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of headache, nausea, and vomiting. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals papilloedema and dilated pupils bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Migraine","Tension headache","Raised intracranial pressure","Cluster headache","Sinusitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eraised intracranial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E, including headache, nausea, vomiting, papilloedema, and pupillary dilation. These findings indicate increased pressure within the skull, which can be due to various causes such as a mass lesion, haemorrhage, or hydrocephalus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine\u003C/strong\u003E presents with unilateral throbbing headache, often accompanied by photophobia, phonophobia, and sometimes aura. While nausea and vomiting can occur, papilloedema and pupillary dilation are not typical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension headache\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a bilateral, band-like pressure sensation around the head. It does not usually cause nausea, vomiting, or neurological signs such as papilloedema or pupillary changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headache\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with severe unilateral pain, often around the eye, and may be accompanied by lacrimation and nasal congestion. It does not cause papilloedema or pupillary dilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESinusitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause headache and facial pain, often with nasal congestion and discharge. It does not cause papilloedema or pupillary dilation, which are indicative of raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Papilloedema is a sign of increased intracranial pressure and requires urgent evaluation.","Headache, nausea, and vomiting are common symptoms associated with raised intracranial pressure.","Pupillary dilation can indicate significant neurological compromise and warrants immediate attention."],"references":["Patel, S., Maria-Rios, J., Parikh, A. et al. Diagnosis and management of elevated intracranial pressure in the emergency department. Int J Emerg Med 16, 72 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12245-023-00540-x","Tripathy S, Ahmad SR. Raised Intracranial Pressure Syndrome: A Stepwise Approach. Indian J Crit Care Med. 2019 Jun;23(Suppl 2):S129-S135. doi: 10.5005/jp-journals-10071-23190. PMID: 31485121; PMCID: PMC6707500.","Kareemi H, Pratte M, English S, Hendin A. Initial Diagnosis and Management of Acutely Elevated Intracranial Pressure. J Intensive Care Med. 2023 Jul;38(7):643-650. doi: 10.1177/08850666231156589. Epub 2023 Feb 19. PMID: 36802976; PMCID: PMC10302390.","Canac, N., Jalaleddini, K., Thorpe, S.G. et al. Review: pathophysiology of intracranial hypertension and noninvasive intracranial pressure monitoring. Fluids Barriers CNS 17, 40 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12987-020-00201-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60339"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60339"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T15:04:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T15:04:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10491"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCou